##PSYCHOLOGICAL CRISIS INTERVENTION IN EPIDEMIC SITUATION: Rescue operation connected by telephone line

Wechat, boyangcongpeople

The function introduces, peels off the human shell, records the real sensible life. Presented by the in-depth Reporting Department of the Beijing News.

The parents of one of the interviewees were diagnosed and were in two separate hospitals, and she had to travel from hospital to hospital to attend to them. She had just come from her father, who was very ill, and was downstairs in the ward, and was on her way to another hospital to be with her mother for the injection. "I don't know if my dad will be here when I get back, " she said, crying on the phone

By Zhang Huilan, Beijing News

This article is about 6086 words long and takes about 12 minutes to read

For nearly 10 days, Du, 49, has heard various cries:

Some sobbed, some wailed, some told stories of themselves and their families, and as they went on they began to choke, and some seemed calm, but she could imagine, the person on the other end of the phone is quietly crying..

Du Mingjun is the Permanent Secretary General of the Hubei Association of Psychological Counselors (hereinafter referred to as "Hubei Association") . He is a 7-year-old psychological counselor based in Wuhan. On January 23, the same day that the Han corridor was closed, the association decided to open a psychological hotline to provide psychological intervention for people in Wuhan, Hubei Province and the country as a whole.

Since the outbreak of the new crown pneumonia, a number of psychological counseling institutions, including the Department of Psychology of the Beijing Normal University, the women's psychological counseling platform "Xingzhi Online" , the association of Psychological Counselors, and the departments of college psychology departments have set up hotlines to help, to provide psychological support to people who are in psychological crisis due to the outbreak.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Passengers wear face masks at Hankou Railway Station in Wuhan, China, on Jan. 22. Photo / Beijing News

On January 27, "the State Council's Working Mechanism for joint prevention and control of COVID-19 pneumonia" issued the "guiding principles for emergency psychological crisis intervention in COVID-19 pneumonia, the local prevention and control headquarters are required to lead the work of psychological crisis intervention in the epidemic situation, and provide the necessary organizational and financial guarantee.

On January 28, the second day after the opening of the hotline of the Psychology Department of Beijing Normal University, the Ministry of Education issued a notice requiring provincial education departments to actively promote the practice of Beijing Normal University, set up specialized teams, and set up psychological support hotlines and Internet counselling services.

Among the many people seeking help, there are first-line medical care, as well as new coronavirus infection and family members, but the vast majority of ordinary people affected by the epidemic. They may have just taken off their protective clothing when the hotline was called, may be on their way to care for their loved ones, may have been isolated for many days. Many of them are faced with a reality that a therapist can't solve, but many of them, before hanging up the phone, will recover and say, "okay, I'm going to do what I'm going to do. "

Crisis Intervention under epidemic situation

The founder of Xingzhi Online, Pan Xingzhi, received a call for help from a nurse. It was January 22, and the nurse had contracted the new coronavirus a few days earlier during a debridement operation on a lung cancer patient, after which she began to feel fear and anxiety.

Such sentiments are common to many of Wuhan's frontline health workers. They're too busy treating patients to think about it during the day, and then they come home at night, feeling anxious. Du also heard a nurse crying, saying he would "cry one after another" after work.

In Du's view, medical personnel have high professional and psychological qualities and will not call for help unless they have to. But in the face of a threatening epidemic, their mental burden is often difficult to imagine, once the opportunity for breathing, the urgent need for psychological crisis intervention.

"different from daily psychological consultation, psychological crisis intervention refers to the unconventional psychological treatment of people's psychology, behavior, health and social panic after a crisis event, " said Dai Zhengqing, a professor of psychology and Director of the Expert Committee of Hubei Association of the Wuhan University. In order to ensure the effectiveness of psychological crisis intervention, many platforms have been strictly screened for the connection of consultants.

Since the launch of the program, more than 500 volunteers have signed up, many of them with a consultant's certificate or social worker's certificate. But many people have no experience of crisis intervention. So the platform chose dozens of consultants to help, and trained other volunteers in crisis intervention as a backup.

The hotline of the Psychology Department of Beijing Normal University also requires the consultant to have experience in crisis intervention, and the first-line consulting experience should be more than 300 hours. All of the consultants sent by the Hubei Association are over 40, Du said. "Only if you have accumulated a certain amount of life experience can you support people of different ages, such as people who have never had children, who may not be able to empathise with a mother's anxiety. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A consultant from the Hubei Heart Association answers the help line. Photo courtesy of the respondents

The day the infected nurse asked for Pan's help, Gong Xing, a consultant, joined the psychological intervention for the nurse. Gong said the nurse's body temperature was as high as 39 degrees Celsius and her eyes were sore from the heat. "She couldn't eat during the day, and she couldn't sleep all night. She was still living in a dormitory in the hospital, so she didn't have to worry her family or tell them, and she was all alone with this huge, inexplicable fear. "

The next morning, Gong and another consultant and two platform staff set up an escort team to provide psychological intervention for the nurses. "A situation like this is definitely the first step, " explained Gong, who soothed the nurse's feelings by telling her that anyone experiencing something like this might panic, a common reaction. Gong also reassured her that, according to available information, the critically ill were mostly middle-aged and elderly people or people with underlying diseases. "You won't have much problem. " The nurse slept soundly that night.

From Du's point of view, Gong Xing's words embody that this psychological crisis intervention is different from the ordinary consultation, as the counselor should store a large amount of knowledge about the epidemic situation, and pay real-time attention to the epidemic situation and national policies, that's how you get through to the person who's asking for help.

Over the next week, the nurse experienced two mood swings over a sudden rise in temperature and an argument with her boyfriend. Gong Xing and others with her to do meditation, to give timely listening, comfort, the nurse's psychological state is more and more stable. "When we are all together with her, her feeling of loneliness will fade away, " Gong said.

On February 1, a nurse told Gong that she had almost recovered and would be discharged in three days.

A war without guns

Du's longest phone call, 44 minutes, came from a suction doctor at a hospital in Wuhan.

It was New Year's Eve, and he had only been minutes from hanging up the hotline and returning to his table when the phone rang again. A frazzled female voice came from the microphone. She said she was at the front line of the Department of Respiratory Surgery. There was a long line at the fever clinic that day. She had been at work for nine straight hours and had just returned home, too tired to turn on the lights.

Without waiting for Du Mingjun to ask a question, the female doctor poured out the words he had been holding in her stomach. She says she doesn't drink water for most of the day because she's afraid to use the bathroom, and only takes a sip from her water bottle when she's too hoarse to speak. Days of intense work have disrupted her body, and every night, she needs to take 1-3 tablets of Valium to fall asleep.

The woman doctor said that she was about to retire, can step aside completely, the child also asked her not to go to the front. But looking at the flood of patients flooding into the hospital, while she stayed behind, she "couldn't do it. ".

In addition to being exhausted, the woman doctor was also anxious. She said there was a high risk of infection among health care workers in patients with fevers because of the potential for infection. She couldn't write her medical history on a computer screen, so she had to take it off. Many elderly patients have poor hearing, so she had to put her mouth to their ears to communicate with them, when the other person answers, it will be close to her ear, and there is no stopping the spray. She and her colleagues were given only one set of protective clothing, which was supposed to be changed every four hours. They write their name on the suit, disinfect it after work, hang it in the ventilation, and wear it again the next day.

He lists in his head three psychological interventions: listening, responding and clarifying, she said. Listening is listening to the person's description of his or her situation, emotions, feelings, and thoughts; responding is affirming the other person's values and beliefs; and clarifying is helping the person to recall and organize resources that can help him or her on a rational level.

As soon as the woman doctor finished talking, Du responded, affirming her sense of responsibility, paying tribute to her and her colleagues on behalf of all Wuhan residents, saying, "we are together, fighting this war without guns on different fronts. ". The woman doctor paused. "Yes, we are too hard. "

As he clarifies, Du guides the woman doctor to reminisce about the past and remind her of the difficulties she has successfully overcome. Slowly, she felt a sense of calm and relaxation in her voice. "The mood and state are enough to sustain her current job and life. "

At the end of the call, Du asked the woman doctor to make him some food. The woman doctor thanked him. "I feel much more relaxed after saying this. It's better than eating anything. "

But he knows that if he hangs up the phone and sleeps a few more hours, the woman doctor will return to the battlefield in her disposable protective suit, which has been repeatedly disinfected. Another nine-hour day with no water and no toilets awaits her.

At the other end of the line, counselors have to empathize with the person asking for help and put themselves in the person's shoes. Lin Xiuyun, director of the hotline in the Psychology Department of Beijing Normal University, said that before the hotline was opened, they originally planned to have consultants work every six hours. However, on the first day, some consultants reported that the intensity was too great, and they adjusted the shift to every three hours. Zhang Liyun, a team supervisor at Xingzhi Online, also said that for counselors who have a lot of contact with people seeking help, supervisors are constantly concerned that "if there are any emotions or problems, they will immediately intervene. "

It's too much to handle on my own

Since the hotline opened on January 23, Du has found that front-line medical personnel are not the main group seeking help. As of January 28, she had received more than 150 phone calls, about 95 per cent of which were from ordinary citizens in Wuhan, Hubei and other provinces.

Just after 7 am on January 28, Du, who was on duty in Wuhan, received a call from a strange woman: I can't take it anymore, I'm falling apart. After only a few words, the lady burst into tears.

On January 19, the woman said, her father was diagnosed with the new coronavirus, a serious condition due to his own diabetes and High Blood Pressure; a few days later, her mother was also diagnosed with a less severe condition. Both parents are in their 70s and in two hospitals. She was the only child of her family, and she was running between two hospitals every day because she couldn't get a nurse.

She had just come out of her father's room to buy breakfast and was standing downstairs when the call came through. She told Du that after feeding his father breakfast, he had to rush to another hospital to accompany his mother who had received the injection. "I don't know if my dad will be here when I get back, " she said, crying on the phone

In addition to worrying about the loss of a loved one, she was also terrified for herself. In the ward with her father, she had little protection other than a mask. She had children of her own, but for the sake of their health, she was separated from her family. She burst into tears. "What should I do if I get infected? My family is going to die! "

In such a situation, Du wanted to know who else was around to help her, but when asked, he found no family or friends to support him. "So you are the most important person in your family, and you need to hang in there so that you can take better care of them, " Du said, urging the woman to go to dinner, "because behavioral changes can support psychological improvements. "

By the end of the call, the lady had calmed down. But Du was not reassured and forwarded the woman's call to another consultant for long-term follow-up. During a follow up visit over the next few days, the woman said her father was out of danger and that she was much better off herself.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Du Mingjun works in front of his computer on January 30. Photo by Ma Jun, Hsinking Daily News

Even if no one in the family is infected, ordinary people will panic in the face of an epidemic. Many people call the counseling hotline simply because they are troubled by the fear, anxiety, and powerlessness of the epidemic.

A consultant at the hotline of the Psychology Department at Beijing Normal University answered a phone call from a Beipiao girl who said her father and brother began coughing and that she and her mother also had high fevers after she invited her family in Wuhan to visit Beijing on Jan. 18.

After going to the hospital, the doctor thinks this family of four is just common cold, not new crown pneumonia. But the girl is still restless, daily self-criticism, that parents on their way to the airport may have been exposed to new coronavirus infection.

Beijing Normal University Psychology Department hotline supervisor Lin Xiuyun Analysis, the girl and her family's physical problems in the stress of the uncomfortable symptoms, is a normal phenomenon. The counselor begins to guide the girl away from the guilt and focus on what she can do right now that is meaningful. "So she walked out quickly, " Lin said.

"A lot of people call in a single person, and they tell the hotline what they are afraid to say to their loved ones and can't say, " Du said, adding that many young people from other parts of the country who work in Wuhan called the hotline and said they wanted to go home to visit their families, but there's no going back. They don't want to worry their families, they don't want to tell them the truth about their situation, "they can't get in, we can't get out. "

A young man on the phone said he wanted to cry. "A man can cry, " he consoled, and he burst into tears. He said such moments moved her the most, and she sometimes wept silently on the other end of the phone.

There are psychological rescue, medical rescue and economic rescue

Those seeking help face not only negative emotions, but also the real problems caused by the epidemic. The latter leaves the consultants feeling powerless.

Nearly all consultants on the platform have received calls like this: Masks are not enough, supplies are not enough, beds are not enough... a Wuhan resident asked Du Mingjun: I only have one mask at home, what should I do? Du Thought of the neighborhood and asked if it was giving out masks. The other side said that the community told a person can only take a mask, "wear a mask out, then throw away, and then take a mask back, it is better not to go. "

Zhang Xiaokou, a consultant with the association of Psychological Consultants in Xianning, received a request for help from a Xianning man. When he returned to his hometown in Shanxi Province with his daughter before the Spring Festival, the man said, he was quickly quarantined at home by neighbors and communities because the license plate was from Xianning. His 5-year-old daughter, who has a fever, has no mask at home and little to eat. He told Zhang that he was "on the verge of collapse. ".

Zhang can help him analyze ways to solve these problems. He can turn to the community and the government for help in terms of living materials. He can go online to find an online doctor for a child with a fever, or he can ask the relevant departments to coordinate. "But I'm not sure if this method will work either. We can only try to guide them. We don't know the final result, " Zhang said.

As a result of the suspension of public transport in Wuhan, many residents suffering from underlying and mental illnesses are in dire straits.

Some depressed patients called the hotline of the Hubei Association of the heart, saying that they had to go to the hospital every week or two to get prescription drugs, and now the drugs are running out, I don't know what to do; some cancer patients asked their counselors for help, saying that they had to go to the hospital regularly for chemotherapy, and now they can't go; There are elderly patients to the hospital on a regular basis to review diabetes Mellitus, now review is also broken.

In such cases, Du would do his best to help those who needed help. If the hospital where the other person was treated had a partnership with Hubeixinxie, she would transfer the call. "But more often it's just suggested they call 110 or 120. There's no other way. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A woman drags a box on her bicycle as public transport is suspended along the Yangtze River Boulevard in Hankou, Wuhan, China, on Jan. 29. Photo / Beijing News

Following the outbreak, the crisis intervention hotline of Wuhan's Mental Health Centre, heartwarming, was opened 24 hours a day. According to statistics released by the center on February 1, in the hotline calls for help since the outbreak, "real-life problems during the epidemic (supply of medicine, travel, diagnosis, medical treatment, food masks, etc.) " is the top of the list of people seeking help.

On January 27, the center released the "new pneumonia" psychological crisis intervention (Wuhan Proposal) " (hereinafter referred to as the proposal) , said that the basis for effective psychological intervention includes: government epidemic notification open, transparent, timely; To ensure the demand for medical materials and necessities for the citizens, the transportation of the people running the city, and the care for the vulnerable groups. The proposal also calls for the government to go first in the face of "such a major social crisis" .

"although psychological crisis interventions are usually targeted at individuals, the effects are focused on groups, because public health events do not affect one person, but rather society and the country as a whole, " Dai said, under this premise, the ideal psychological crisis intervention should be under the guidance of the national law and policy, and be deployed by the central government, which includes psychological rescue, medical rescue and economic rescue.

For people with PTSD

Recently, the consultant of the Hubei Heart Association received a call for help. A man said that his mother-in-law had been admitted to the intensive-care unit due to a new coronavirus infection. When his wife accompanied her mother, she saw that a patient had died and was carried out wrapped in a white cloth, and I saw patients who were waiting for a bed that they couldn't get, start attacking doctors. Later, his wife was also diagnosed with a new coronavirus, she was extremely scared, worried about themselves and their mother will encounter misfortune.

The man said his wife has been stressed out lately, thinking "is it that pneumonia again" whenever someone coughs around her, and has nightmares at night about the horrible things she sees in the hospital during the day.

According to Dai, the man's wife had exhibited classic symptoms of Post Traumatic Stress Disorder. But the man said his wife is now refusing to accept psychological help, he is very worried, called to ask for help. After talking to a counselor, the man decided to learn some counseling to calm his wife's nerves.

Zhang Liyun, a psychotherapist at Xingzhi online, is also seeing signs of PTSD. In her group, a Wuhan resident said a patient in the next building had been "dragged away" by 120. "The word she used was 'dragged away, ' not 'picked up, ' 'taken away, ' and so on. It may not matter to her now, but it could become a traumatic scene for her later, " Zhang said.

Zhang, 49, has been in counseling for more than a decade. In 2008, she was involved in post-earthquake counseling in Wenchuan County, and in 2013 in post-earthquake counseling in Ya'an. When the danger comes, people do not pay attention to their deep psychological needs, so there is no large-scale PTSD population, Zhang said. She estimates that a large number of PTSD patients should emerge after the epidemic, before the first line of care that has been replaced may develop symptoms of PTSD "in late February or late February. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Reuters / Bobby Yip sanitation workers clean up an empty street in Caidian District January 28,2010. Photo / Beijing News

Dai Zhengqing believes that the potential PTSD population includes new pneumonia patients and their families, health care workers, first-line volunteers, and even the front-line civil servants.

"after the disaster, it's time to deal with a lot of psychological problems, " Tang Jun, director of the Child Rehabilitation Department at the Wuhan Mental Health Center, told the Beijing News, train psychotherapists on how to deal with possible psychological problems after a disaster.

Du also thought of this. She said that the Hubei Heart Association has begun to prepare for post-disaster psychological rescue, is currently collecting and collating typical cases and problems, for the next stage of psychological assistance guide. In the future, counselors from the Hubei Heart Association will also be involved in helping people with PTSD. "depending on the circumstances of each person seeking help, some people can receive online counseling and some people must do it offline. "
